	affiliations = {University of Mannheim, Germany},
	abstract = {This chapter develops the concept of administrative resilience in order to strengthen the administrative state in light of its current systemic challenges. Based on interdisciplinary approaches, the chapter defines resilience as the ability of an actor to overcome adversity and revert to a state of equilibrium with their functioning and integrity intact. Resilience thus adopts an intertemporal perspective of complex systemic challenges. In addition to its positive contribution, the concept of resilience has a normative function. It draws attention to mechanisms that can help entrench higher normative goals, such as democratic legitimacy, adherence to the rule of law, or the effective provision of public goods. Moreover, it emphasizes the need for an institutional and legal framework for administrative actors that incorporates resilience by design. Accordingly, this chapter explores three central lines of inquiry to which administrative law scholarship should dedicate attention: the ongoing technological transition from rule-based to predictive administration; the internal structure of administrative organizations; and the role of information for administrative actors. In conclusion, it emphasizes the potential of a resilience framework to endow administrative actors with the tools to address systemic challenges. © 2024 selection and editorial matter, Susan Rose-Ackerman; individual chapters, the contributors.},
