	affiliations = {Global Institute of Business Studies, India},
	abstract = {This study examines ethical risks in AI- driven finance, including algorithmic bias, transparency deficits, and accountability gaps. Through a systematic literature review (PRISMA 2020) and thematic analysis of 100 peer- reviewed studies, it is revealed that minority loan applicants face rejection rates 2.5 times higher than those of their counterparts with identical financial profiles. Opaque "black box" models hinder regulatory oversight, exacerbating systemic risks (e.g., 2010 Flash Crash). Case studies (Apple Card, deepfake fraud) highlight regulatory fragmentation and generative AI threats. The proposed Ethical AI Governance Matrix integrates technical audits (SHAP, IBM Fairness 360), dynamic regulatory sandboxes (EU AI Act), and stakeholder collaboration (ethics boards). Recommendations include mandatory bias audits, cross- border data treaties, and participatory design to strike a balance between innovation and equity. Findings emphasize the need for urgent interdisciplinary action to prevent market instability and amplify inequality. © 2026, IGI Global Scientific Publishing. All rights reserved.},
