	affiliations = {Department of Public Relations, Bolu Abant Izzet Baysal University, Bolu, Turkey},
	abstract = {This section addresses the transformation of the basic skills required to participate effectively and consciously in social life in the digital age. While digital literacy was initially defined by the capacity to access, evaluate, and produce information, today, with the rapid spread of artificial intelligence technologies, there is a need to go beyond this concept. Therefore, artificial intelligence literacy is taking shape in a way that includes citizens with basic awareness and critical thinking skills about algorithms, data processing processes, and automated decision systems. The transition from digital literacy to artificial intelligence literacy requires not only an increase in technical knowledge but also a deepening of ethical, social, and legal awareness. In this context, individuals need to understand how artificial intelligence systems work, question how these systems affect their lives, and access information that will enable them to defend their rights. The section aims to draw theprofile of the digital citizen of the future by examining the differences between digital and artificial intelligence literacy, transition processes, and examples of policies and education in this field. Finally, suggestions are presented for empowering citizens as conscious, participatory, and ethically responsible individuals in the age of artificial intelligence. © 2026 by Nova Science Publishers, Inc. All rights reserved.},
