	abstract = {Administrative and constitutional law, as well as wider legal principles complement European Union data protection legislation in balancing various fundamental rights and interests in automated decision-making in public administration. This chapter will, from the administrative law perspective, with a de lege ferenda emphasis, further develop a legal-certainty-based framework on automated administrative decisions. Finland's legislative proposals and constitutional practice, complemented by comparative perspectives from legislation and doctrine in Germany, France, and Sweden, and U.S. Federal administrative law, will be used in the analyses. European law recognizes a right to human review. The role of legislation is to set general but sufficiently guiding requirements on the design of automated systems and procedures. The chapter concludes that legislators, system-developers, and those who apply the law have a common task to maintain human dignity and human agency in the face of automated public administration. © The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2023. All rights reserved.},
