	affiliations = {University of Amsterdam, State Councillor with the Administrative Jurisdiction Division of the Dutch Council, Netherlands; Tilburg University, Netherlands Scientific Council for Government Policy (WRR), Netherlands},
	abstract = {This chapter focuses on the role of AI in the procedures and administration of courts. The authors discuss a range of possibilities and opportunities that appear realistic within the next few years, including applications for business operations and the further strengthening of the quality of judgments. The potential use and implications of generative AI, such as ChatGPT -by courts but also attorneys and litigants - are also considered. In outlining options, the authors do not suggest that all of them should necessarily be implemented. The choice of whether an application is to be used will ultimately depend, among others, on what might be called a ‘moral compass’. The authors set a tentative step towards the development of such a compass, taking account of principles of due process, the core values of the judiciary, and criteria specifically related to the application of AI, such as the need for transparency, explainability and accountability. © The Editors and Contributors Severally 2024. All rights reserved.},
