	year = {2026},
	journal = {International Journal of Human Rights},
	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1080/13642987.2026.2630719},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032551834?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Law Department, University of Tabuk, Tabuk, Saudi Arabia},
	abstract = {The concept of the rule of law is similar to the idea of ‘good’ in that it enjoys universal support. However, a major impediment to the rule of law is emerging through the proliferation of artificial intelligence (AI) technologies. As AI progresses in the academic realm, it is being increasingly integrated into digital decision-making systems in many countries, supplanting human decision-makers. An illustrative case is the use of AI to help judges resolve cases. Nevertheless, this technology often operates as a ‘black box’ because of its intricate nature and legal protections, rendering it opaque. The resulting lack of transparency and the complexity of these systems pose a threat to traditional rule of law principles, such as accountability, transparency, explainability, and fairness. This study delves into the impact of AI on the rule of law, shedding light on the adverse consequences for humanity. It explores the diminishing role of the rule of law as AI becomes deeply embedded in society and it raises questions about its viability in a technocratic society. © 2026 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.},
