	affiliations = {Texas A&M University, School of Law, United States; Yale Law School Information Society Project, United States; NYU School of Law Policing Project, United States},
	abstract = {Law enforcement has an opacity problem. Police use sophisticated technologies to monitor individuals, surveil communities, and predict behaviors in increasingly intrusive ways. But legal institutions have struggled to understand-let alone set limits on-new investigative methods and techniques for two major reasons. First, new surveillance technology tends to operate in opaque and unaccountable ways, augmenting police power while remaining free of meaningful oversight. Second, shifts in Fourth Amendment doctrine have expanded law enforcement's ability to engage in surveillance relatively free of scrutiny by courts or by the public. The result is that modern policing is not highly visible to oversight institutions or the public and is becoming even less so. Copyright © 2021 Hannah Bloch-Wehba.},
